Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.132; μουσική 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 668b; τιμαί [prev. author] “R.” 519d; σπέρματα 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.4.23 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δῶρον οὐ σ. εἰς ὄψιν not <b>goodly</b> to look on, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 577 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τραγῳδία σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Poetica” 1449b17; σ. ὑπόδημα [prev. author] “EE” 1219a22 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:— a play on senses [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.1 and 11.2 in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1176b25, 1177a3 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ironically, σ. χρῆμα a <b>fine</b> thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Mercurium” 332. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>adverb</i> σπουδαίως <b>with haste</b> or <b>zeal, seriously, earnestly, well</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.3.9, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 406b, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>comparative</i> <b>-ότερον</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.3.20 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>-οτέρως</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Nob.” 15: _superlative_ τὰ -ότατα\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] <b>most carefully, in the best way</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.86.—Besides the regular _comparative_ and _superlative_, we find in _Ionic dialect_ the forms -έστερος, -έστατος, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.8, 133, 4th-5th c.BC: Hecataeus Milesius Historicus cited in 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 1441.15, 4th c.AD: Eusebius Myndius Philosophus 4. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G4709","accentedUnicode":"σπουδαίως","relatedNos":[{"strongNu